\par 
\par }{\fs20\insrsid4065019 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 In this document SA officers are setting out the main political questions for the relaunch of the SA on 12 November 2005 under the following headings. 1) Politics and aims    2) A campaigning allia
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 nce  3) Relations with the socialist movement  4)  The Socialist Alliance and the SGUC, Respect and the LRC  5)  Structure and constitution
\par }{\b\fs20\insrsid4065019 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 1.     Politics and aims 
\par 
\par }{\fs20\insrsid4065019 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 The new Socialist Alliance is an alliance for republicanism, internationalism, socialism\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  and the environment. [As identified in aims of the SA(p) clauses A4 \hich\f0 \endash 
\loch\f0 \hich\f0  A7 -  see note in appendix on Arise ]. The new Socialist Alliance is pro-party and will campaign for a \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 republican socialist party along the lines of the Scottish Socialist Party\'94\loch\f0 . [As
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 identified in aims of the SA(p) clause A3]. 
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 \hich\f0 The new SA continues to stand on the 2001 SA programme \'93\loch\f0 \hich\f0 People Before Profit\'94\loch\f0 
 until such time as it is updated and amended. If the new SA is successfully launched then it should begin a review of PBP for consid\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 eration at a future SA conference.
\par 
\par }{\b\fs20\insrsid4065019 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 2.  A campaigning alliance
\par 
\par }{\fs20\insrsid4065019 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 The main focus of the old SA was electoral work. This should not be the defining characteristic of the new SA. We should build on the basis of campaigning activity. We should be able to exist 
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
as a campaigning organisation with or without electoral activity. There are sound reasons for retreating from electoral work. First we are now a much smaller organisation with a much narrower and more uneven base. Second we need to change our own attitude
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
from the previous tendency to electoralism towards building a campaigning base. Electoral activity should be an extension of campaigning work not a substitute. The initiative for standing candidates should come from local SA branches. But we should keep t
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 h\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 e situation under review.  
\par }{\b\fs20\insrsid4065019 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 2.1  Local campaigns 
\par }{\fs20\insrsid4065019 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Our main activity should be building branches with emphasis on socialist education and campaigning work. We should distinguish between national campaigns led by the national SA organisation and local camp
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 aigns initiated by SA branches and relating to local issues. A local SA is free to campaign on local issues as it decides for example around a local hospital, against housing policy or in support of a local strike etc.  
\par 
\par }{\b\fs20\insrsid4065019 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 2.2  National campaigns
\par }{\fs20\insrsid4065019 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Campaigns\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
 promoted and supported by the national alliance involve national events such as demonstrations, or national conferences. But they need to be supported in the localities and carried into the local labour and progressive movements. Our aim is to encourage 
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 l\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 ocal SA\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s to incorporate SA national campaigns into their local work.     
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 We have identified five political areas in which we want to develop national campaigning work \hich\f0 \endash \loch\f0  on the need for party, republicanism, internationalism, socialism and the environmen
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
t. We have three convenors on Republicanism (Mike McNair), Internationalism (Nick Rogers) and the Environment (Tony Twine). This should be the starting point for establishing Standing Committees with the task of developing campaigning work in each area. I
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 n\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  some cases we may seek to launch new campaigning initiatives. In other cases the SA may be able to build on activity already being done by SA members. 
\par }{\b\fs20\insrsid4065019 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 2.3  Campaigning for a new party 
\par }{\fs20\insrsid4065019 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 One of the central SA campaigns should be on the issue a new working\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
 class party. We need to produce national material making the case of a republican socialist party along the lines of the Scottish Socialist Party. This is a campaign that has to be carried into the socialist and trade union movement.       
\par }{\b\fs20\insrsid4065019 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 2.4  Campaig\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 ning on internationalism 
