\par }{\b\fs20\insrsid4065019 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 3.  Relations with the socialist movement
\par 
\par }{\fs20\insrsid4065019 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 At the present time the socialist movement is reorganising itself into four coalitions/alliances - Labour Representation Committee, RESPECT, the SGUC and the Socialist \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
Alliance. These represent different policies and perspectives for the working class movement. The SA exists not only because we have the longest record (12 years) of fighting for socialist unity but also because we have something distinct to say about the
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 direction the socialist and working class movement should take. 
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 The SA is the only alliance or coalition campaigning for a new independent working class party. We are the only alliance campaigning for republicanism, internationalism, socialism and the en\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
vironment. This is not to deny that both Respect (\hich\f0 \lquote \loch\f0 E\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0  for environment) and SGUC (\hich\f0 \lquote \loch\f0 G\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0  for Green) or that \hich\f0 \lquote \loch\f0 S\hich\f0 \rquote 
\loch\f0  is for socialism in \hich\f0 \lquote \loch\f0 Respect\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0  and \hich\f0 \lquote \loch\f0 SGUC\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 
. We are the only alliance campaigning for a republican socialist party along the lines of the SSP. The LRC\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
is for rebuilding the Labour Party and neither Respect nor the SGUC campaign for a new working class party. The SA has a distinct message whilst not denying some areas of political overlap with the other alliances.    
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 We have to explain to the working cl\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
ass movement the importance and significance of the political direction we are proposing. At the same time we have to ensure this does not degenerate into sectarian rivalries. Whilst we cannot account for the behaviour of the other alliances, we are accou
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 n\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 table for our own actions. 
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Our general attitude to these rival alliances should be governed by the policy of the united front. First we are in favour of united action with all these organisations against capitalism and the Labour government. We do not pl
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
ace our differences with these organisations above the need for a united front against the common class enemy. This means we put the interests of the working class for unity above any special policies or interests we hold against other socialist coalition
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 s\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 . 
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
The united front policy does not mean the suspension of criticism. On the contrary it means we act together whilst continuing to explain our policy differences. The purpose of the united front is also educative. It is to enable the working class to und
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 erstand the policy differences and which ideas and policies best represent their interests. To hide our differences in the united front is to prevent or undermine the political development of the working class.      
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 The high point of this united front wo\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 uld be the merging of the LRC, RESPECT, SGUC and the Socialist Alliance into an independent working class party \hich\f0 \endash \loch\f0 
 which in our view should be a republican socialist party along the lines of the SSP. Such a party would seek to develop the closest relations\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
with the SSP and socialists in Wales and Northern Ireland and as far as possible aim to form a single party.  
\par }{\b\fs20\insrsid4065019 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 4.  The Socialist Alliance and the SGUC, Respect and the LRC
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 4.1  The SA and SGUC
\par 
\par }{\fs20\insrsid4065019 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Of the four alliances [Labour Representation Committee, RES\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
PECT, the SGUC and the Socialist Alliance] it should be clear that the SGUC and the SA exist in the same political space outside the Labour Party and Respect (with exceptions). A merger of the SA and SGUC into a single alliance would be step forward. But 
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 t\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 his is unlikely to happen in the short term because they represent different campaigning priorities and perspectives.     }{\b\fs20\insrsid4065019 
\par }{\fs20\insrsid4065019 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 The SGUC is an electoral alliance of affiliates. The SA is (planning to become) a campaigning alliance, based on individual membersh\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
ip with affiliates. The main issue behind this is the relationship between the SA and the Socialist Party. 
\par }{\b\fs20\insrsid4065019 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 4.2  The SA and Respect  
\par 
\par }{\fs20\insrsid4065019 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 The 2005 general election has established Respect as the main alliance of socialists outside the Labour Party and in opp\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
osition to it. The relative success of Respect in winning a parliamentary seat and the subsequent appearance of Galloway in Washington has established Respect as the main alliance. Whatever our differences with Respect or predictions about its future demi
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 s\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 e we have to begin by recognising its position.
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 SA members have a range of views about Respect. Some are Respect members. Others have joined and left. Others have never been members. It should be remembered that the SA Democracy Platform made the major in
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 tervention at the founding conference of Respect when we proposed Respect adopt republicanism, no immigration controls, MP\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 
s on a workers wage [check -   ] All these policies were rejected. Current SA members were also prominent at the second Respect conf\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 e\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 rence arguing for secularism.  
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 It was not clear at this time whether Respect would survive the 2005 general election. That question has now been resolved. The SWP has now committed itself more firmly to the future of Respect. We can expect Respect to rem
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 ain an important factor on the left until at least the next general election. We have to review our attitude and relationship to Respect in that light. 
\par }{\b\fs20\insrsid4065019 
\par }{\fs20\insrsid4065019 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 It would be easy and tempting to define ourselves primarily in the negative as the \hich\f0 \lquote \loch\f0 anti-Respect\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0  alli\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
ance. This would be a serious and sectarian mistake. We are first and foremost against capitalism and the Labour government and Labourism as an ideology, which undermines the ability of the working class to defend itself. We must not loose sight that our 
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 m\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
ain purpose to build working class opposition to the Labour government. In this we stand for specifically socialist unity. We are an alliance for republicanism, internationalism, socialism and the environment. We are fighting for a republican socialist pa
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 r\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 ty along the lines of the SSP. 
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Therefore in pursuing our aims we stand independently of Respect. Our relationship to them should be governed by the united front against Labour and capitalism. Whether this united front is \hich\f0 \lquote \loch\f0 theoretical
\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0  or \hich\f0 \lquote \loch\f0 practical\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0  will\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
 depend on the size of the SA membership and the forces that coalesce around the SA (e.g. affiliates). It does mean that we should respond to proposals from Respect and be prepared to make proposals to Respect (open letters etc). At the same time we must 
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 c\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 ontinue to fight for our own independent aims.   
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 The next question is whether we should intervene inside Respect as well as outside as an independent organisation. This is a tactical question. But given the relative size of Respect and the SA, and the ex
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
pected growth of Respect, it would be a mistake not to intervene on inside in fighting for our policies and a new party. We already have SA members inside Respect, particularly our CPGB members and other comrades. But these have operated as CPGB members o
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 r\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  independents. We should now take a decision to intervene inside Respect. Whether we do so in the name of the SA or not is a tactical question.  
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0    
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 The relationship of SA members to Respect will depend on circumstances. SA members are autonomous. Joining\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
 or not joining Respect would remain a personal decision for individual members. In terms of the local situation both the SA and Respect are distributed unevenly in geographical terms. In some places Respect is dominant and in others it hardly exists. In 
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 s\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 ome places for example in Reading we should fight to build the SA. It is a matter for local SA\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s to determine their attitude taking account of local circumstances.
\par }{\b\fs20\insrsid4065019 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0     
\par }{\fs20\insrsid4065019 \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Respect claims to be the alliance for the whole socialist left despite the lack of inte\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
rnal democratic structure and practice. [See Respect conference 2005]. It occasionally makes appeals to non-Respect socialists to join its ranks. It would be wrong to rule out such a possibility. However there would have to be negotiations over the terms 
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 a\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 nd conditions. The SA should not officially \hich\f0 \lquote \loch\f0 join\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0  without negotiations first.    
